<br>
Her life was a lie.  Her world was deceit.  The simple cleanness of hate, tainted.  Honor, a facade she had hidden behind for a long time.  Creapiing idly swirled her fingers in the red pool on her desk.  Her own blood, was tainted.  She nodded to herself, as if to agree with her own thoughts.  One could not cleanse the dishonor of generations from ones blood.  If her grandfather had been the man her Mother said, then she had no honor in her blood, no chance at filtering out the deceit.  Odd, how the ink slowly congealed like blood.  Her fingers swirled about more.<br>
<br>
Creapiing wiped her hands on a cloak, the red stain would stay for some time on her hands, but she would not leave fingerprints.  But her mark, the mark she would leave, all would know.<br>
<br>
Creapiing called in her assistant.  I was gone but a short time, she lied.   One of my servants spilled ink on my desk.  Assemble them now so we can find out who the careless one is.  Her assistant scurried off, looking like she would kill whoever had done this to her masters office.<br>
<br>
One by One, the servants appeared.  Her assistant had brought in the guards, who now stood blocking the doors.  Fully 20 people, including guards, assistants and servants now stood in her office.  Is this everyone?  Her assistants angry face looked over the group and she said, Yes, this is all of them. Let the culprit stand forward.<br>
<br>
Creapiing grasped her weapon firmly.  <br>
<br>
None who who had served her, none who knew her secrets, none who had access to her ways, not one must live.  She motioned to the guards to not allow any out of the room.  Her assistants voice was a distant hum.  Her blade bit through her assistant cleanly.  Surprise on every face.  Creapiing swiftly went to her work.  As the last servant fell, Creapiing, muscles aching, drooped.  Then, giving no forewarning, she fell upon the two guards as well.  They fought well, but they were no match for the Reaper.<br>
<br>
Creapiing slid out of her armor.  She dropped her weapon.  She removed her boots, her cloths, and stood naked in the carnage.  Carefully, she spread equal amounts of the blood and red ink over her body.  She used a dagger to slash off her hair.  Her face she scratched with her own nails.  Her mane of white hair she left on her desk.<br>
<br>
Stumbling out the door, she left her office, ignoring the gasps and stares of those out in the street.<br>
